english:
  title: Farewell to Kim Jik-jang
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The ways a gentleman may bring joy to his parents are many, yet the civil service examination stands foremost among them. Since the Tang and Song dynasties, those endowed with great talent and noble virtue have risen from remote villages to grace the court, their accomplishments and renown illuminating their own age and casting light upon posterity—all by traveling this very path.

    When such a man first arrives, clad in simple robes with a wide sash, singing the songs of recognition, he is but an obscure mountain dweller. Yet once he enters the examination halls and ascends the palace steps to hear his name proclaimed, he gains fame in a single day and receives the Emperor's favor from the nine-fold palace. In time he becomes a minister, a duke, a prince. Through this rise, his parents leap and dance with joy, marveling that such excellence sprang from their own embrace—this is the common desire of all humanity.

    But when brothers both capture top honors and claim places in the highest rank together, this is something neither China nor our Eastern realm has witnessed before. The parents' joy must exceed all ordinary celebration—it is not merely one family's blessing, but the glory of an entire province, nay, the radiance of the entire nation.

    The brothers Kim of Gimnyeong are distant descendants of King Suro himself, and sons of the venerable Elder who once served as Collector of Rites. From childhood, nurtured by household teachings, they grew learned and eloquent, earning the admiration of their peers for many years—twin stars, each bright as the other.

    In autumn of the year Imjin, after our Prince honored the tomb of the Former King and performed due rites at the Confucian Temple, he ascended the Hall of Virtue and commanded a great examination. The imperial decree had long circulated, so scholars from all quarters flooded the capital like clouds, their brushes at the ready to discourse on the principles of governance. When the examiners had completed their selection, barely eleven were chosen—yet both Kim brothers passed, with the younger achieving first place and the elder ranking second. When His Highness reviewed their papers, he elevated both to the highest category. Of the first rank, only two were named, and the Kim brothers occupied both—no other could compete. Like wild geese flying in formation, like brocade banners vying in splendor, they have set all ears and eyes astir. Their ascent has been swift: the younger appointed Inspector of the Censorate, the elder to his present post as Director of the Royal Wardrobe.

    Alas, how generous heaven proves to our venerable Elder! The youngest brother, though unsuccessful this time, has already earned distinction in the capital examinations and shall surely take first or second place in the coming spring, continuing his brothers' glory. Should fortune delay a year or two, we may await him with confidence. Thus the Kim household's blessings have not yet reached their end.

    Moreover, through fourteen years of fostering learning and cultivating talent, our Prince's efforts have borne fruit precisely in this moment. Is this merely one family's, one province's glory? No—it illuminates the entire realm.

    As the year drew to its close, the brothers petitioned to return home to Cheongdo to honor their parents. The land suffered famine, and customarily all examination graduates would forgo public celebration. Yet the Prince, in special grace, permitted them to feast at the provincial hall, bringing joy to the parents and extending honor throughout the district.

    Did not Confucius say: "When you establish yourself and bring honor to your name, your parents are glorified"? These brothers have already accomplished what few can achieve—they stand established, their names are known, their parents exalted. Should they not then consider how to repay the sovereign's grace?

    The ancients said of themselves: "My life's aspiration lies not in comfort and plenty." As counsel to others, they offered: "Only practice sincerity and truthfulness throughout your days." I know well the brothers' integrity and steadfast conduct. Let them strive to match the ancient sages, redoubling their efforts beyond measure. What need have they of another's guidance or encouragement?

    I, Jong-jik, grow old. Lonely and precarious my path, I shamelessly hold office still. Yet I hear of Ningchuan's hermitage calling to me—apes and cranes beckon. Should I journey southward and pass through Cheongdo, I shall recite verses of the auspicious cedar and golden laurel of that blessed place, and offer prayers for the Elder's long life.
  footnotes:
    - The "Deer Song" (鹿鳴) references the Book of Poetry and was traditionally sung at civil service examinations, symbolizing the recognition of talent.
    - The brothers' simultaneous success in the highest civil service examination rank (甲科) was an extraordinary achievement, as the text emphasizes.
    - The references to immortals (apes and cranes) and the hermitage reflect the poet's own desire for retirement, a common theme in classical Chinese and Korean literature.
    - The final verses allude to the cedar (靈椿) and laurel (丹桂) as auspicious symbols traditionally associated with parental longevity and familial blessing.
